WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.491
A mixture is what happens when substances are together,
but not chemically rebuilt into one new substance.

2
00:00:06.491 --> 00:00:12.515
Think of cereal and milk. The cereal is still cereal. The
milk is still milk.

3
00:00:12.515 --> 00:00:21.102
That is different from a compound. In a compound, atoms of
different elements are chemically joined in a fixed
arrangement.

4
00:00:21.102 --> 00:00:27.243
Water is not a loose pile of hydrogen and oxygen. It is a
new substance with its own properties.

5
00:00:27.243 --> 00:00:34.099
Mixtures can be obvious: sand and pebbles, cereal and
milk, paper clips and rice.

6
00:00:34.099 --> 00:00:43.226
Some mixtures are less obvious. Salt water looks clear,
but salt particles are spread through the water. That kind
of mixture is a solution.

7
00:00:43.226 --> 00:00:50.113
Dissolved does not mean gone. If sugar dissolves in water,
the sweetness tells you the sugar is still there.

8
00:00:50.113 --> 00:00:56.034
Dissolving sugar is a physical change. The sugar is spread
out, not rebuilt into a new substance.

9
00:00:56.034 --> 00:00:58.910
Chemists separate mixtures by using properties.

10
00:00:58.910 --> 00:01:07.687
If pieces are different sizes, use sieving. A sieve can
separate pebbles from sand because the holes care about
size.

11
00:01:07.687 --> 00:01:14.824
If an insoluble solid is mixed with a liquid, use
filtering. Filter paper can catch sand from muddy water.

12
00:01:14.824 --> 00:01:23.366
But filtering will not remove dissolved salt from water.
The salt particles are too spread out and too small for
normal filter paper to catch.

13
00:01:23.366 --> 00:01:30.464
For salt water, use evaporation. Let the water leave as
vapour, and the salt can be left behind.

14
00:01:30.464 --> 00:01:40.565
If one part is magnetic, use a magnet. A magnet can pull
iron filings from sand. It will not help with rice,
because rice is not secretly metal.

15
